THE RISK:
{
 "id": "ce-hyperscale-flow-mirage",
 "title": "Year-1 hyperscale demand lands in Ireland, Sweden and Belgium — the 0.44 CE slice is a global split painted on the wrong map",
 "narrative": "seg.hyperscale rescales Synergy's global 44–48% capacity share onto Central Europe via a flat 0.91 carve-out. But ~60% of Europe's operational hyperscale self-build capacity sits in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden and Belgium — three of the four outside CE-7 entirely, and the fourth banned from new hyperscale construction. The 2026 self-build wave (4.2 GW, +24% YoY) will follow existing land banks and secured grid positions, i.e. mostly outside the venture's geographic scope, while inside CE-7 hyperscalers consume capacity as colo pre-lets procured through global frameworks. The model's largest segment is substantially a demand flow the venture cannot geographically reach in Year 1, and the 'sell to large operators first' strategy is aimed at it.",
 "category": "model-structure",
 "targetNodes": [
  "seg.hyperscale"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "European hyperscale self-build additions of 4.2 GW in 2026 (+24% YoY) concentrate where the operational base already sits: ~60% in Ireland, NL, Sweden, Belgium as of Q4 2025",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c12",
    "digest:seg-mix#c14"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Within CE-7 the two plausible hyperscale destinations are gated — NL closed to new hyperscale builds outside two municipalities, Frankfurt queued 24–36 months — so CE's realized hyperscale share of the Year-1 demand flow runs well below the flat 0.91 rescale of the global split",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-NL#c7",
    "digest:geo-DE#c15",
    "ledger:seg.hyperscale"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "seg.hyperscale at 0.44 overstates the in-scope segment; the overstatement propagates into the large-operator buyer cell the venture leads with, compounding the channel-mix uncertainty already flagged there",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.hyperscale",
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The node is marked triangulated across multiple Synergy vintages, and the trajectory (41→48%) is genuinely well-evidenced — but every vintage is global. The flat 0.91 carve-out looks like a conservative haircut, so the review instinct is satisfied; nobody asks whether the geography of hyperscale capacity is itself skewed away from CE-7, because the ledger has no node where that question lives.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "A Europe-scoped capacity split (CBRE, Synergy custom cut, or DC Byte) showing CE-7 hyperscale-operated share at or above ~0.40, or two-plus announced 2026 CE-7 hyperscale self-build campuses breaking ground outside the NL exception zones.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.42,
  "rationale": "The 60% concentration outside CE-7 is a hard Q4-2025 datapoint and the CE gating mechanisms are enacted; uncertainty remains because hyperscalers also occupy CE colo capacity (leased, not self-build), which partially preserves the segment's PDU demand inside scope. [evidence revision: The core Q4-2025 concentration datapoint and the 4.2 GW/+24% figures are now independently confirmed by two CBRE-sourced reports, hardening the trigger premise. However, an emerging CE-region signal (WBS Power's grid-secured 3.2 GW campus in Poland) shows hyperscale self-build activity is beginning inside CE, partially offsetting the 'venture cannot reach it' framing, and no source directly quantifies CE-7's hyperscale-operated share to fully resolve the model-impact step. Net effect is a modest upward nudge from 0.40.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "seg.hyperscale",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.32,
   "note": "CE-realized hyperscale slice shrinks in absolute terms; not a mix shift to siblings — the demand flows to geographies outside scope"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "CE-7 share of new European hyperscale self-build MW",
   "where": "CBRE European data centre quarterly updates; DCNN/DC Byte self-build geography breakdowns",
   "threshold": "CE-7 receiving <15% of new self-build MW over two quarters",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Hyperscaler campus announcements and permitting filings inside CE-7",
   "where": "Google/Microsoft/AWS EU infrastructure press; German and Polish municipal permitting dockets",
   "threshold": "Zero new CE-7 self-build campus starts over two consecutive quarters",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Commission a CE-7-scoped segment split (hyperscale/colo/enterprise by MW) as a custom cut from Synergy or DC Byte",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "seg.hyperscale",
   "note": "Directly replaces the global 0.91 rescale with regional data"
  },
  {
   "action": "Rebalance the Year-1 pipeline toward colocation and enterprise cells that are physically located in CE-7, deferring the hyperscale motion until regional presence is proven",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "New hyperscaler capacity to outpace colocation in Europe",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Data Centre & Network News (CBRE data)",
   "date": "2026-02-19",
   "excerpt": "Hyperscaler self-build capacity across Europe is expected to reach 4.2GW this year, representing 24% year-on-year growth. As of Q4 2025, approximately 60% of Europe’s operational hyperscaler self-build capacity is located in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Belgium.",
   "url": "https://dcnnmagazine.com/business/real-estate/new-hyperscaler-capacity-to-outpace-colocation-in-europe/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "CBRE: European hyperscaler self-build capacity growth to outpace colocation supply growth",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "DatacenterDynamics (CBRE Europe Data Centres report)",
   "date": "2026-05-06",
   "excerpt": "CBRE's report, which covers Q4 2025, predicts hyperscaler self-build capacity will reach 4.2GW in 2026... with 60 percent of Europe’s operational hyperscale self-build capacity located in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Belgium.",
   "url": "https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/cbre-european-hyperscaler-self-build-capacity-growth-to-outpace-colocation-supply-growth-but-supply-outpaces-take-up-in-weaker-than-expected-2025/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "WBS Power Advances 3.2 GW Energy Infrastructure for Hyperscale Data Center Campus",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Gulf Oil and Gas",
   "date": "2026-03-24",
   "excerpt": "A new hyperscale data center campus with a target capacity of 3.2 GW will be developed in Lublewo... in northern Poland... WBS Power S.A., which has already secured grid connection conditions for the full 3.2 GW capacity.",
   "url": "https://1156-799.el-alt.com/webpro1/main/mainnews.asp?id=1112920",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://dcnnmagazine.com/business/real-estate/new-hyperscaler-capacity-to-outpace-colocation-in-europe/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "As of Q4 2025, approximately 60% of Europe’s operational hyperscaler self-build capacity is located in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Belgium."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/cbre-european-hyperscaler-self-build-capacity-growth-to-outpace-colocation-supply-growth-but-supply-outpaces-take-up-in-weaker-than-expected-2025/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "This new supply will be delivered across nine European countries, with 60 percent of Europe’s operational hyperscale self-build capacity located in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Belgium."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/hyperscale-operators-to-account-for-67-of-all-data-center-capacity-by-2031",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "they now account for 48% of the worldwide capacity of all data centers. Almost 60% of that hyperscale capacity is now in own-built, owned data centers with the balance being in leased facilities."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://1156-799.el-alt.com/webpro1/main/mainnews.asp?id=1112920",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "A new hyperscale data center campus with a target capacity of 3.2 GW will be developed in Lublewo, in the municipality of Choczewo in northern Poland's Pomerania region."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.cbre.com/insights/reports/global-data-center-trends-2026",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "Global power availability and grid infrastructure constraints are impacting development timelines and site selection, especially in established hubs in North America (Northern Virginia, Chicago) and Europe (London, Frankfurt)."
  }
 ]
}

